If you want a metaphor from the experience of mammals like us... The squash isn't the baby. The squash is the womb. The seeds are the babies.

If you end up with a zucchini/pumpkin/etc mixed up by squash, it's because the seed you grew had an unexpected pollen donor last year. It has nothing to do with what other squash are growing nearby this year.

If you're growing squash and the fruit are shaped differently than expected, it's not because that flower was pollinated by another variety. Assuming full pollination, the fruit shape is only a manifestation of the mother plant.(Poor pollination -> distorted, shrunken fruit.)

More importantly, the question is how to translate probability and magnitude of risk of a rare event (e.g. emergence of a viral 'variant')into policy. Interestingly the 'precautionary principle' that has often been invoked in that context is actually utterly useless.6/
This might shed some light on the possibly enigmatic - and arguably somewhat flippant  - recent comment by Neil Ferguson that he was happy to be wrong as long as he was pessimistically wrong.5/

Predicting risk is indeed super tricky and as a consequence an understandable pressure on those who have to predict risk is to err on the side of caution, i.e. "better safe rather than sorry", even when they appreciate they may end up way off with their predictions.4/

Essentially anything and everything is possible, though some events are more likely to happen and some are worse. This makes risk assessment difficult. In essence the question becomes how can we weight both the impact, and the likelihood of something bad happening. Tricky!3/

It's also possible that SARSCoV2 could become more virulent than ebola and MERS, it could spread through the human population like wildfire, and send humanity back to the stone ages. It's possible, it just happens that the associated probability to this event is ridiculously low.

Essentially anything's possible. It's possible that if I bought ten lottery tickets in a row, I could win the jackpot with every single ticket, ten times in a row. It's possible, it just happens that the associated probability to this event is ridiculously low. 1/

This combined ML/pharmacokinetic approach lets you simulate alternative dosing intervals, and works well with mistimed doses or blood samples. It also estimates patient pharmacokinetic parameters rather than being an opaque box.

The current #StateOfTheArt of machine learning in #precisiondosing usually means predicting the exposure from a fixed dosing schedule. This works well for consistent data - but in practice, dose/sample timing get messy, plus you lose mechanistic insight (like drug clearance).
Using our machine learning models to predict when a patient wasn't well-described by our pharmacokinetic models reduced our prediction error by 12‚Äì22%!

We discovered we could identify when Flattened Priors were more predictive by using machine learning. We tried a bunch of different features, but the most important ones showed good agreement with our clinical intuition üòÅ https://t.co/kcBOjNdUvh

What happens if you listen more closely to the data for these outliers - or in slightly more stats-y words, "flatten" the prior distribution.Flattened priors (FP) is better in some patients, but in others, predictions that listen *too much* to the data can be *way* off. https://t.co/LVYvEUXGDl

The model prior acts kind of like an anchor ‚öìÔ∏èpreventing predictions from straying too far from our priors until we have enough evidence to believe otherwise.This is usually helpful, because clinical data is messy...... but sometimes outliers are meaningful!

In Bayesian model-informed precision dosing (#MIPD), you combine info about the average patient (model priors - usually a population pharmacokinetic model; green lines) with observations about that individual (black dot) to predict how that patient will respond (blue/gold lines). https://t.co/tsNAwZigMj

As many have commented, the structure isn't the end goal, but rather the beginning of understanding. So in that sense it comes back to "some models are useful". But maybe we at some point have to stop dividing up structures into three pools (predicted, integrative, experimental)

Right now, I agree that there is a qualitative difference between "pred" and "exptl" structures. But the last decade+ of integrative structural biology has shown that these areas are merging, and with improved computational methods entering the field this will get even more murky

Objection 5:The AF/etc structure doesn't look like the exptl structure, it must be wrongComment:It likely is. But, there's also the chance that the exptl structure is wrong, or doesn't represent the state that biology (aka evolution and MSA) cares about

Objection 4:OK, I buy the DNA sequencing argument, but then you're looking at the "avg" structure of the familyComment:This is a very valid concern, and needs to be addressed further (there's already some work). How well do these methods distinguish related proteins?
Objection 3:It's only an experimental structure if you had a (pure) sample of the proteinComment:What about structures from cryo-ET or in cell NMR
Objection 2:But they rely on some physical/statistical model and not just dataComment:Engh & Huber values, force fields, statistical potentials are also used in "normal" structure determination
Objection 1:But they aren't based on experimental dataComment:Yes, they are. They are based on DNA sequencing experiments.
This is mostly meant for discussion trying to go beyond the quick "all models are wrong but some are useful" view
Provocative take:Models such as those generated by AF/RoseTTAFold/etc are as much "protein structures" as those from traditional biophysical experiments

Based on this clustering @Ally_Dunham found 100 AA "sub-types" which is a lower bound estimate given the small number of proteins studies. We can study their properties and frequency: ex charged amino-acids only care about charge in around 20-30% of positions. https://t.co/ywSWW7ZFrq

As an example, we can see that positions from 3 transmembrane proteins separate according to their properties or how structural and evolutionary properties relate to the DMS mutations. This suggests that the data can be clustered to find amino-acids functional groups. https://t.co/Tiqbta4CfL

I wish that the government would have made one final push to get as many people vaccinated as possible, particularly by reaching out to those that delay acceptance or refuse vaccines. Nobody can rely on the herd for protection. #GetVaccinated /6 & end

In conclusion, I don‚Äôt think there is (and may never be) complete, protective herd immunity to COVID-19. The most important intervention to reduce the risk of serious illness and death is getting vaccinated. The vaccines are safe and effective. /5
There may thus be no such thing as herd immunity to COVID-19, until a vaccine that provides sterilising immunity is developed. However, this is technically very complicated, perhaps impossible. /4

Currently, sterilising immunity is not achieved by vaccination against or prior infection with COVID-19. Symptoms in vaccinated individuals will be generally be mild. They will, however, still be able to transmit the virus, putting unvaccinated individuals at risk. /3

Herd immunity can be achieved when vaccines (or prior infection) give complete protection (sterilising immunity) against (re-)infection and onward transmission. Measles is an important example here where this can be achieved through vaccination. /2

I am concerned about the repeated use of the term ‚Äòherd immunity‚Äô in the context of COVID-19 by policy makers and the media. I fear that some that refuse vaccinations are doing this because they feel they will be protected by the herd. This is wrong and dangerous. /1

In conclusion, giving children a vaccine against a disease that is quite harmless to them, and for which the long-term risks are unknown, is extremely reckless.  Even more so, given that we will soon have a vaccine available, for which long-term safety is much more established.

The children may also see their grandparents, who can have some risk, even if vaccinated. However, if this is a worry, the children can simply be tested, or take other precautions. At least until they have acquired immunity through natural infection, or from a future vaccine.

But maybe if the health benefit to others is sufficiently large. However, this health benefit doesn't seem very large at all. The main risk will be to the parents. But parents with teenager children are usually not that old, plus they are vaccinated. So their risk is minimal.

This argument does not appeal to me. Children have longer time to live, and health effects therefore have a larger impact on them. I don't like the idea of risking the health (and even possibly future reproductive health) of children, for some health benefit to others.
Another argument put forward is that the vaccines are not given for the benefit of the children themselves, but to protect their nearest.

But more importantly:2. The choice is not between one of the new vaccine types and covid. The choice can be between a new vaccine type, and a traditional vaccine, such as Novovax.Novovax is based on a technology that we have used without issues in flu vaccines for many years.

The counter-argument to this is that covid infection can have unknown long-term side effects too. To which I would say 2 things:1. It seems quite unlikely for children, given the unserious case of disease they develop.

And this is just the short term effects. It is possible that the vaccines have unknown damaging long-term effects too. This is especially true for mRNA vaccine technology, for which there doesn't exist any data for long-term use.

Of course for older people, these risks of side effects are easily worth it. But children have extremely low risk from covid. Quite possibly lower than the risk from vaccination, especially for Astrazeneca which is the one suggested in the article.

These vaccines have shown an extremely high number of side effects compared to previous vaccines. (A few percent, compared to 0.05% for flu vaccines.) The side effects include serious things such as thrombosis and myocarditis.

Slow down on adding fancy features. Focus on provable correctness. It will be a huge challenge. But the only alternative is to accept that the bad guys will always be able to get into your phone or computer, whether it's international hackers or your own elected government.6/6

If Pegasus exists, what else may exist out there? Anything really. Operated by anyone.How to stop them? Legal means won't work beyond a point. Software should be provably correct, secure by design, written in safe languages, auditable, subject to enormous stress testing. 5/6

Linux (and MacOS) date in their philosophy to Unix and C from the 1970s. It was a very different world. The best minds across corporations, academia, and the free software world must think about how to re-engineer and re-architect EVERYTHING for this post-Pegasus world. 4/6

The best minds in security are trying constantly to break OS's and find holes and fix them. But so are the best minds among bad guys (that includes NSO and various "intelligence agencies"). How to stay ahead of the game? I don't know but... 3/6

There is an effort to enable using Rust in Linux. It would not be a rewrite but an alternative language for writing device drivers etc. That's good but nowhere near enough. Nobody knows how many holes existing and are already being exploited, how many are undiscovered. 2/6

One lesson from Pegasus has to be stepping up security of operating systems. iOS, Android, Linux, MacOS, Windows, the lot. Just this week is another local root hole in Linux, dating to 2014. It is a hard problem. C is a terrible language for security-conscious programming. 1/6

Finally, I hope more details are made available soon and the committee does not allow its position to be defined by the public pronouncements of particular members. 10/n

Thus in principle, I don‚Äôt think they are closing the door in the long run to vaccination for protecting others. I don't know what the process for revisiting this decision would be but the sooner that occurs, the fewer would have been unnecessarily exposed to covid risk. 9/n

They also seem open to the principle of allowing an individual to be vaccinated in order to protect others, while making it clear that they and their families must be fully informed of the decision they would be taking. 8/n
So in a sense, JCVI is implicitly in agreement with MHRA that these are incredibly safe vaccines, that they are prepared to allow large numbers of people take. 7/n

More importantly, given that, although the vaccine won't be rolled out to all 12-18s at this stage, it will be rolled out to hundreds of thousands in particular vulnerable, or living with particular vulnerable, individuals. 6/n

With adolescents living with vulnerable parents being offered the vaccine. So the door is open to community transmission also being included in these kinds of calculations, and its not clear why, and who, explicitly excluded this from the terms of reference. 5/n

More curiously, the remit specifically appears to preclude risk in terms of community transmission, and risk to others more generally. However, and this is an important exception - risk to vulnerable parents is factored in, 4/n

Of course, these calculations leave out the risk of long term health consequences such as long covid. We are well past the point where the possibility of long term disease needs to be factored into policy. 3/n

This is conjecture, but it appears that these are calculated over a particular time horizon, and don't factor in the possibility that the overwhelming majority of under 18s will certainly encounter the virus at some point over the coming year on current policy trajectory. 2/n

On the JCVI decision, the real question to my mind is who sets the terms of the question being asked for this group, and what precisely they are. It appears the prime criteria are individual hospitalisations and deaths risks, though other factors are considered in part. 1/n

If this happened, immune-escape strains of the future might be both marginally less transmissible AND less virulent. That said, I wouldn't count on it ...7/

If we're really lucky, the increased selective pressure to bypass host immunisation might eventually entail an evolutionary tradeoff for the virus, with a 'replication cost' paid by future immune-escape strains.6/

As the pandemic progresses, the selective pressure  on SARSCoV2 will shift from higher transmissibility in naive hosts to bypassing immunity in immunised hosts (provided by prior infection and/or vaccination).5/

SARSCoV2 Morbidity/mortality has gone down drastically thanks to an increase in the proportion of the population being immunised. This trend is expected to continue, but not because SARSCoV2 lineages in circulation are becoming intrinsically less virulent.4/

All else being equal, more transmissible lineages are better at infecting and replicating within host cells. When viruses replicate they kill host cells. As such, it should not come as a surprise that the alpha and delta variants are both more transmissible and virulent.3/

It is often assumed that there must be a tradeoff between virulence and transmissibility. This is actually relatively unlikely for SARSCoV2, given that it is only moderately lethal and that ~50% of transmissions are from a/pre-symptomatic people.2/https://t.co/2KUEF3Y9vl

Viral transmissibility is multifactorial. It depends on the virus, host-pathogen interactions, and host behaviour upon exposure. The relation between transmissibility and virulence is not straightforward, and the two can be both negatively or positively correlated.1/

This is most obviously true about recent mixed race individuals - but we are all "mixed race" if we want to have this be about biological, genetic things - all mongrels, all have complex ancestries at some point in our genetic's history because that's how... humans work.

The logic mistake is to place skin pigmentation into a very different category of visible differences that is somehow meaningful compared to hair colour, height or other things - ie, if I know your skin colour, what else can I work out? It is surprisingly... little.

An appeal to many people who might read this thread and say "yeah, but, let's face it, people are different, I can *see* these differences, and we all have to accept these differences". Nothing here negates this "obvious" statement which one can see.

Back to the "adapted" word - human skin pigmentation has been distributed worldwide partly due to adaption, but it is (a) not an important adaption now (modern vitamins etc) and (b) does not extrapolate *in any way* to other features or groups.

Furthermore obsessing about skin pigmentation is as sensible as using hair colour or height (We don't say - you are very tall, do you have Estonia heritage? No, please, tell me more about your Irish heritage because with that red hair, it must be somewhere in your family).

One only needs to think of recent "mixed race" individuals - from Barak Obama through to Dele Ali to David Olusoga - but this "mixing" has happened all the back across the Afro-Caribbean community and the long history of Black British in Liverpool and Cardiff.

This mixing is ... mixing. It means look at someone's skin pigmentation is not a good proxy for the rest of their genome, even if it is not random with respect to history, it is just not "useful" to predict other parts of the genome.

The second thing is that we keep on moving and mixing. Due to horrible, utterly wrong processes, like slavery. Due to curiosity of explorers, like Portugese. Due to shiphands to Liverpool. Due to economics and war, like Somalis in London. Due to religion. It is endless.

An ever better piece of news, primarily for people in rich countries, is that we have built up superb surveillance capacity to monitor viral evolution and have highly effective vaccines that can be updated to keep up with the evolution of the virus when it will be required.13/

The bad news is that we won't get rid of SARSCoV2 anytime soon. The good news is that once it has become endemic, morbidity and mortality is expected to be dramatically lower, roughly in line with the other endemic seasonal respiratory viruses infecting us on a regular basis.12/

Indeed, even when neutralising antibodies in the blood have waned to low levels, or are unable to  effectively bind to the new viral strain, the host is still protected through cellular immunity (T-cells) and memory B-cells that churn out antibodies.11/

The primary reason why the other ~200 respiratory viruses in circulation don't currently cause  morbidity/mortality comparable to SARSCoV2 is that most people have been infected by them, generally early in life, and in the case of flu, vaccines also help. 10/

While this all may well sound like a doomsday scenario, it is roughly what we already experience for most of the ~200 endemic seasonal respiratory viruses, including seasonal flu (influenza A/B) and the four globally distributed seasonal endemic coronaviruses.9/

This is an important point because almost all SSDs promote performance and don't talk as much about what they're rated for in terms of longevity. Great on a gaming PC, not ideal for backups.It'll cost you ~$100 to try to recover data from an HDD. SSDs will cost you > $1000.

4/ Never buy used SSDs.A 256GB SSD on a Mac would be rated for about 150 terabytes written (TBW). Manufacturers say they'd last for up to 600 TBW, but I wouldn't trust this.My usage is about 2TB written per week, which means I can expect to reliably use it for < 2 years.

3/ MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures). Eg: Sandisk extreme has an MTBF between 1.4 - 2.5 million hours.So if you take 1,000 of this particular SSD running 8 hours a day, one of those drives will fail every 175 days!1.4 million hours / 1,000 drives / 8 hours per day = 175

2/ Don't store your SSDs for too long. Store them in good conditions when you do.Last I checked, a powered-off SSD will hold its data for about 2 years.If you do use SSDs for backups ‚Äì power them up and access the data every now and then.

1/ Not all SSDs are made alike, you really pay for reliability with these things.One reason; almost all consumer SSDs, Sandisk extreme etc, are made using NAND TLCs (#3) with 500-2000 write/erase cycles. Intel makes enterprise SLC (#1) SSDs that can handle 50000-100000 cycles.

We  recommend health institutions to monitor the Delta variant constantly and to warn about the dangers that it poses when social interactions are done in high-risk environments. End 14/

Europe now faces the possibility that, despite the presence of high vaccination rates, an important load in the health care system due to COVID-19 materializes. In Barcelona, incidences in the younger cohort are around 3% and hospital admissions are rising /13

In Europe, younger cohorts are not vaccinated. The large increase in Rt associated with younger cohorts can lead to 4% incidences in the 20-40 age bracket when a Delta can sustain Rt at 3 for a couple of weeks.Typically, 2% of these cases reach the hospital.  12/

However, any growth, even a slight one, can put a lot of pressure in primary care at least. If the growth is not stopped relatively soon, hospitals will follow with a relatively large number of hospitalizations 11/

If restrictions are lifted in high risk environments, the Delta variant can produce huge increases in incidences very fast. Once a region reaches high incidence, it is more difficult for the epidemics to grow, given the huge amount of mixing required to sustain it 10/

The introduction of the Delta variant has worsened markedly the epidemic evolution in Barcelona. The increase in transmissibility around 60% from the Delta to the Alpha variant in the Barcelona surge of cases has important implications for the future. 9/

In Barcelona city (right) Rt reached 2-2.5 for the alfa variant, but above 3.5 for the delta. In the northern metropolitan region Rt was around 4.5-5 for the delta variant. This difference is very important. Due to delta, cases more than quadrupled in one week 8/

Delta variant presents a 60-65% increase in transmission compared with the alfa variant. The join effect of the increase in transmission with the presence of high-risk environments for this transmission lead to Rt around 3-4. Here our estimations for each one of the variants 7/ https://t.co/TJkeEgvzp4

It happens that I'm not a dictator and have no ambition to become one. Having essentially no control over the situation, and not really knowing what I'd do if I were the dictator anyway, I'll simply conclude that this is a bit of a mess.6/

Alternatively, as a dictator, I could pretend that everyone who had covid had their brains melted and their hearts shattered. This may likely improve care and treatment for those who need it, but would also increase the nocebo component of long-covid.5/

If I were a dictator in charge of all of you, I could claim long-covid isn't a thing. This would be an obvious lie and people suffering from it would not get adequate care and treatment. That said, if most believed me, I would limit the nocebo component of long-covid.5/

A determinant of the psychosomatic component of covid is the nocebo effect, i.e. the fear of being at risk making us unwell. For example, people in the control arm of the Pfizer trial reported fatigue (33%) and headache (34%) despite not having been injected with the vaccine.4/

There likely is a psychosomatic component to long-covid, which is as painful to the individual, and as costly to society than any 'mechanistically caused' disease. The difference between psychosomatic and non-psychosomatic disease can be very grey, and all disease is real.3/

Long-covid is currently poorly defined and comprises short-term minor inconveniences as well as long-term debilitating symptoms. It would help if the scientific community could coalesce on a meaningful clinical definition (e.g. 'precluding normal activities after 3 months').2/

Long-covid poses an exceptionally challenging public Heath problem. It is real. We've known for many years about post-viral syndrome and full recovery from any severe infection (e.g. sepsis or TB) takes time, and is not always complete.1/

The prokaryotic and viral communities in Manatee Springs clustered by site, w/ seasonal variability driven by flow. Microbial community composition was affected by changes in physiochemical parameters and community coalescence, with evidence of species sorting and mass effects.

The abundance of prokaryotes and viruses increased 100-fold from the spring head to the river and few members from the head communities persisted in the river, suggesting the springs play a minor role in seeding downstream communities.

The new @AppEnvMicro paper looked at spatiotemporal variability within Manatee Springs - comparing the spring head where water emerges from the aquifer, a mixed region where the spring run ends, and a downstream site in the Suwannee River, 4 times in a year. https://t.co/XdCsS1YZGh

Kema's PhD research, funded by @NSF DEB-1555854 and a GRFP fellowship, provided key baseline information. Her first paper in @mbiojournal showed that different springs have unique prokaryotic and viral communities, likely driven by springshed composition https://t.co/zY495hVNOj

The Floridan aquifer system is a major drinking water source and feeds large amounts of freshwater to river systems, yet surprisingly little is known about the prokaryotic and viral communities in Florida's freshwater springs - which provide a window to the aquifer. https://t.co/4uSxXBtZKP

These marks are sometimes passed on from cell to cell as cells divide. They can even be passed down from one generation to the next! https://t.co/4xYpzUyztQ

These marks do not change the sequence of the DNA, but they change the way cells use the DNA's instructions. They can change the genome in a way that tells it what to do and where and when to do it! https://t.co/jtkDV2jiJa

The epigenome can attach to DNA and direct its actions, including turning genes on or off or controlling the production of proteins in particular cells. When epigenomic compounds attach to DNA and modify its function, that means they have "marked" the genome. https://t.co/xvGmOxaOAk

The human genome is the complete assembly of DNA, about 3 billion base pairs, that makes each person unique. DNA holds the instructions for building the proteins that carry out a variety of functions in a cell. https://t.co/qDa9BjmmKk

I don't doubt most mean well, even those who wish me harm. Though, neither the 'let it rip' or 'zerocovid' crowd are proposing helpful long-term public health strategies. It would be nice, at least for the tone of the discussion, if more could reflect on this point.6/

One key constraint is to maximise the number of people who are vaccinated by the time they get exposed to the virus for the first time. Though, in order to minimise overall harm to the population, there are other constraints and tradeoffs to take into account.5/

Implementation details vary and different countries have different approaches at their disposal. There's also uncertainty about the effectiveness of various measures. But at the end of the day, essentially everyone has to get immunised to send SARSCoV2 into endemicity. 4/

Such mitigation strategies imply enforcing the lightest possible measures in any place at any time, to ensure the epidemic never gets out of control. This is textbook pandemic management. It put me at times in tune with the zerocoviders, at others with the smileys. So be it.3/

By early 2020, I concluded that the prospect of global elimination of SARSCoV2 was gone. The option left was mitigation of the overall morbidity / mortality caused directly both by COVID-19, and the indirect deleterious effects of the pandemic.2/

I'm getting a lot of abuse on twitter. Currently, I'm in the crosshairs of the Zerocoviders, but attracted similar hate from the smileys at times. What many in those two camps may fail to grasp is that my aims are not aligned with either of them. 1/

But tools exist and should be built into academic research from the start of a student's project, in both computational and experimental work. Not just replication of the final result in a paper but continuous testing.

It's hard to replicate results at the cutting edge of science. Often there is no second person in the lab with the expertise and experience to check your work. Especially a problem in India where most lab members are young students.

This experience was a huge factor in my decision to go to industry, where replication and robustness are built in to the process of research. I didn't want to make (more) avoidable scientific mistakes because of my own inexperience and having no one to check.

I hadn't even heard of such things as version control, unit testing, required code reviews. To my knowledge, no one in my lab was implementing such practices (maybe they were and I didn't know!) But I made many mistakes, some of which I caught just before submitting a paper.

When I was a PhD student, very little of my research was independently replicated or tested before publication. Perfectly understandable; it would be very time-consuming to replicate experiments. But for computational work, it would have absolutely been possible to test.

I would welcome a recognition of the trade-offs inherent to any public health measure, or lack thereof, and an admission that their impact can vary dramatically for different people. I could also dispense with the relentless shaming and fearmongering.6/

Misleading people is counterproductive in the long-term; there should be no room for 'ends justify the means' approaches in public health. Many are prepared to pay a small price as long as it is clear what the benefit may be to others in society.5/

Most academics tend to realise this challenge (up to a point). Though, many will try to address it by either minimising the impact of mitigation measures, or exaggerate the risk of the virus to everyone, irrespective of their age and health. I feel this is misguided.4/

Those incompatible aspirations, expectations and personal situations make it near-impossible to devise public health strategies that satisfy and benefit everyone. The eventual outcome will thus likely be an uncomfortable compromise, despised by many but tolerated by most.3/

At an individual level, there may be no perceived trade-off. A parent of an immunocompromised child may feel that no measure is too stringent to protect them. Conversely, a healthy young adult whose prospects in life are being ruined may dismiss the need for any intervention.2/

Figuring this out and debugging other issues related to the MILP solver has cost me a couple hours already. I'm extremely sympathetic to the need to make money from scientific software -- scientists and engineers should be paid. But there must be a better way to handle this.

Even if you restrict your jobs so they run on a single compute node, then activate the license from that node, the process fails -- the cluster's nodes aren't allowed external network access, so they can't reach the licensing server.

Specifically, the academic license is tied to a single machine's hostname. In a compute cluster running SLURM, where the hostname of the compute node executing your job can't be predicted, this means it's impossible to use the academic license.

Relying on commercial libraries for scientific software is bad, even when those libraries offer academics free licenses. I've been trying to use a commercial MILP solver for a method I'm testing. Even though it offers an academic license, it fails badly for my usage.

The SARSCoV2 T-cell X-immunity saga has been an interesting journey for me. I initially thought it made sense (and got massive abuse for it). I then changed my views to it being probably anecdotal, and now, I'm essentially back to square one. Science is interesting at times.6/
To summarise, there may indeed be such a thing as 'immunological dark matter' against SARSCoV2 üò¨, at least in some people who were extensively exposed to HCoVs pre-pandemic.5/

A major piece of evidence supporting a role for pre-existing T-cell cross-immunity is that T-cell that expanded in those with abortive infection were found in regions of high genomic sequence conservation between SARSCoV2 and endemic coronaviruses in circulation.4/

The primary underlying mechanism of viral clearance in those "exposed seronegative" seems to be preexisting T-cell X-immunity caused by prior exposure to endemic ‚Äòcommon cold‚Äô coronaviruses (HCoVs). Latent exposure to low levels of SARSCoV2 may also have played a role.3/

The study focuses on a cohort of intensively monitored healthcare workers who remained repeatedly negative by PCR and SARSCoV2 antibody testing for 16 weeks post-recruitment, but mounted a robust T-cell response against SARSCoV2.2/

New preprint out. The results indicate that in some people, exposure to SARSCoV2 elicits an innate and T-cell immune response, leading to an abortive infection, without development of antibodies (seroconversion).1/https://t.co/7NUNK5r46h

So, my take:Probably long COVID in kids is not the main factor in deciding how to deal with the epidemic, or to vaccinate kids.But we shouldn't expect it to be a negligible issue either.(Also, this study focuses on 2020. Maybe the impact of Delta could be worse. Who knows?)

Making up some not unreasonable numbers:a wave of Delta engulfing the UK could probably cause something like 5 million infections among kids. They translate to something like 100,000 long COVID cases.And 100,000 families having to cope with that, of course.Not great, tbh.

Not so good news:2% is a small fraction.But small fractions are dangerous when multiplied by large numbers, such as those expected for this wave e.g. in UK.In fact it affects a few % of children WHO GET INFECTED.(Or better, who develop antibodies, which should occur often.)

This is both good and so-so news.Good news:It likely affects only A FEW PERCENT of children who get infected.Maybe ~2% have symptoms for more than 3 months (although numbers in the study are too small to get decent estimates)Less than many feared. Let's hope it'd be true!!

The study is random but without much statistical power given the small number of seropositive kids (109).But if you look at the numbers, it's reasonable to assume that - long COVID exists- it affects only a few % of children who get infected- often disappears before 3 months

Lots of comments on this preprint https://t.co/0jbxvuWrICof a Swiss study on longCOVID in children. Looks like most commenters use it to foster their prejudices, as usual.I am quite agnostic about the matter, so decided to have a look.Overall: it's good news, but not great.

Once a metadata record has been validated through the Majora API, it is immediately visible to everyone in the consortium through the Majora website and APIs https://t.co/nMaIcTbKIQ

But our users are humans, not machines! We want them to be able to upload metadata and get errors back in a friendly way. Luckily @bioinformAnt and @TheCGPS wrote a fancy frontend to the Majora uploader. Users login with OAuth, drag and drop CSVs and see errors in a friendly way. https://t.co/jSQgCaZFYU

Our API endpoints mean that messages about samples can be traded between applications in real-time. Importantly, this means we can give the boring task of checking whether metadata is valid to a computer and get results back immediately. https://t.co/fhHA5999uZ

An application programming interface (API) allows a computer program to talk to humans or other computers, you just send it structured messages in a particular format and you get a message back. Majora does everything through machine-readable APIs without exception https://t.co/0uRsYye9Nw
Here is a thread I wrote about Majora at the end of its launch week all the way back in April last year https://t.co/T81EoEmlzV

Majora is the brain of @CovidGenomicsUK. It's the database that stores all our metadata, and offers a set of APIs that allow the database to be updated or queried. It was written in @djangoproject and unified the entire metadata collection process for COG in three weeks. https://t.co/GnLReavYER

At the intersection between intuitive and portable... spreadsheets! Of course, we need to validate this data. We don't want to process hundreds of spreadsheets by hand, and don't want humans involved in storing or querying processed metadata... Sounds like a job for computers. https://t.co/u1djFw4o7K

We authored a (very) minimal metadata standard to ensure that genomes could be contextualised for a public health response, but without creating too much of a burden. Uploading this minimal metadata needed to be made as simple as possible to support a wide range of users. https://t.co/xzvJFoRqDC

CLIMB-COVID is an isolated system on @MRCClimb, mirrored in @unibirmingham and @cardiffuni. We offer a walled garden to turn sequences around quickly (no waiting for slow public databases), without risking low quality data entering public databases before QC.

The prior funding of @MRCClimb was a prudent investment, setting the scene for the compute and personnel to be readily available to establish CLIMB-COVID so quickly. CLIMB-COVID was built by the triumvirate of UoB's Radoslaw Poplawski, Cardiff's @matt__bull and yours truly

For this to work, we needed; a location (that could be reached by everyone, and store the data we need), a data specification (to apply standards to incoming data) and a database (so we can store metadata and ideally get it back out again)

Our challenge was to build an encompassing digital infrastructure to address the problem of collecting and integrating both genomic sequencing data and sample-associated metadata, from all the autonomous sites producing data in the @CovidGenomicsUK network.

Sequencing sites are independent and use their own expertise, generating SARS-CoV-2 genomes with their own extraction, sequencing and bioinformatics protocols (though many sites have converged to the @NetworkArtic protocols) https://t.co/YRyTCNx2xk
